Good morning. 'This is test one. 'We have 58 year old male for an ERCP with stent exchange, follow up of bile duct structure. 'After confirming informed consent, the patient is positioned in the left semi-prone position, intubated and sedated under anesthesia. 'I now pass the diurnoscope to the mouth. ' advancing carefully through the oesophagus and into the stomach. 'The visualized portions of the oesophagus and stomach appear normal. 'I advance the scope further into the second portion of the duodenum. 'On scout imaging, a previously placed biliary stent is seen with a common bile duct ' the major papilla is identified in the second portion of the duodenum. 'I see a visible stent emerging from the papilla with evidence of a prior sphincterotomy. 'I am using a snare to remove the previously placed stent and the stent removal is successful. ' Next, advance a sphincterotome with a guide wire and achieve easy cannulation of the common bile duct. 'Deep cannulation is confirmed. 'Contrast injection is now performed and the cholangiogram reveals a short, mild stricture in the mid-common bile duct. ' It's consisted with a non-anastomotic structure. 'The appearance is improved compared to prior imaging. 'I'm using a 12mm stone extraction balloon. 'I sweep the bile duct twice. ' I've removed the debris from the duct. 'Contrast drainage is noted though slightly sub-optimal. 'Given the findings, I proceed to place a 10 French by 9 centimeter Boston Scientific ' Advanix Rapid Urinal Bend Piliary Plastic Stent across the stricture site. 'One stent is deployed successfully with good drainage observed. ' Now the scope is completely withdrawn from the patient. 'The procedure is completed without difficulty. 'Estimated blood loss is none and there are no immediate complications. 'No specimens are obtained from the procedure. 'End of test 1.

This is test two. 'This is an ERCP with sphincterotomy and papillotomy performed on December 17th, 2020. 'We have a 49 year old female with a history of primary biliary cholangitis, elevated liver enzymes and chronic pancreatitis. 'She's recently admitted with acute abdominal pain. ' Prior imaging including CT abdominal and MRCP demonstrated pancreatic ductal dilation and structure with the possible pancreatic duct stone in the head of the pancreas. 'After explaining the risks, benefits and alternatives, informed consent was obtained and verified. 'Timeout was performed with the entire team present. 'The patient is positioned in supine position ' and it's intubated and serrated under anesthesia. 'I'm using a Pentax ED3490-TK duodenoscope. 'Now I'm introducing the scope through the mouth. 'It's passed through the esophagus and the stomach. 'Now being advanced into the second portion of the duodenum. ' A scout film obtained prior to scope insertion was unremarkable. 'On endoscopic examination, the stomach appears normal. 'The major papilla is identified in the second portion of the duodenum and is normal. 'Bile noted draining from the orifice. ' The minor papilla is located approximately in the second portion of the duodenum and is normal. 'Initial pancreatic duct cannulation is attempted using a sphincter tom with a guide wire. 'Cannulation is difficult, but superficial access is achieved. ' Bile duct cannulation is being attempted using a sphincter dome and a guide wire. 'We have achieved deep cannulation with ease, performing a cholangiogram. 'It reveals a normal biliary tree without any strictures, dilation or stones. ' With the guide wire in place, a biliary sphincterotomy was performed successfully. 'I repeat pancreatic duct cannulation again using sphincterotome and guide wire. 'Superficial cannulation is achieved and the guide wire is being advanced a short distance into the head of the pancreas. ' The contrast injection reveals a short branching pancreatic duct without upstream filling, suggest a possible stricture or incomplete diversion. 'There's multiple attempts to advance the wire upstream, but it's unsuccessful. ' The main pancreatic duct is scanulated with a tremor catheter. 'However, there is no pancreatic duct visualized with contrast injection. 'The binaural papilla is again examined and it's found to be normal. 'I am slowly retracting the scope. ' scope is completely withdrawn and the procedure is concluded estimated blood loss was none no specimens were obtained and there is no immediate complications thank you

This is test 3. 'We have a 75-year-old male. 'He's come for ERCP with a follow-up history of duodenal polyp. 'He has had prior EOS in June 2020. 'This showed an ampulla 13 mm with increased stiffness compared to surrounding. ' He has also had an ERCP with spyglass in August 2020 which showed normal CBD. 'He is here for a stent removal. 'Informed consent is obtained after explaining the risks, benefits and alternatives of the procedures. ' The patient is positioned in the left semi-prone position, intubated and sedated under anesthesia. 'I now introduce the Pentax ED3490TK diurnoscope through the mouth. 'Advancing it through the esophagus, moving into the stomach. ' The esophagus and the stomach appear normal on entry. 'The scope is then advanced into the second portion of the duodenum. 'The scout film obtained prior to scope insertion is normal and it reveals a biliary stent in situ within the CBD. ' The major papilla is identified in the second portion of the duodenum. 'It shows evidence of a prior sphincterotomy and contains a visible stent at the orifice. 'Wild drainage is observed from the papilla. 'I am using an occlusion balloon with a guide wire. 'I attempt wilder cannulation. 'It is achieved easily with deep cannulation confirmed. ' I first attempt removal of the proximally migrated stent using a stone extraction balloon. 'However, this is unsuccessful. 'Now I am using a rat toothed forceps to grasp and retrieve the stent. ' Now the stent is successfully and safely removed. 'The CBD that is the common bile duct is visualized with good bile flow. 'I see no residual stent fragments or debris. 'I'm now withdrawing the scope from the patient. ' The procedure is completed. 'There is no estimated blood loss. 'No specimens are obtained and there are no immediate complications. 'End of test 3.

Test 4. 'We have a 44-year-old female here for an ERCP, a treatment of abdominal pain of suspected biliary origin, bile duct stones, gallbladder stones, biliary dilation on ultrasound and abnormal MRCP. ' The informed concern is obtained after discussion of risks, benefits and alternatives. 'Timeout is successfully performed with the treatment team. 'The patient is positioned in supine, intubated and serrated under anesthesia. 'I now introduce the PENTAX ED3490-TK Diagnoscope Test. ' scope is in and i'm advancing it through the mouth now moving towards the esophagus entering the stomach the visualized portion of the esophagus in the stomach looks normal ' I'm advancing into the second portion of the duodenum. 'The scout film obtained prior to endoscope incision appears normal. 'The major papilla is located in the second portion of the duodenum and appears normal with bile noted raining from the orifice. 'I'm using a sphincter term and guide wire. ' I am attempting a bile duct cannulation. 'Initial cannulation enters the pancreatic duct rather than the bile duct. 'A small amount of contrast is injected into the pancreatic duct to delineate its course. 'Multiple attempts to cannulate the bile duct are made. ' but the guide wire continues to intermittently enter the pancreatic duct side branch at the level of the head. 'For post ERCP pancreatitis prophylaxis, I place a 5 French by 3 centimeter Boston scientific advex. ' advenex pancreatic plastic stent into the pancreatic duct. 'The stent is deployed successfully. 'I then proceed with pre-cut access using a needle knife papillotomy to gain entry into the bile duct. 'Now deep biliary carination is achieved successfully. ' performing a cholangiogram. 'I see a single stone in the distal common bile duct. 'I see normal common hepatic duct and intrahepatic ducts with no dilations. 'I'm using a stone extraction balloon. ' I'm sweeping the bile duct several times. 'I'm removing a single stone and the removal is successful. ' I see good drainage of bile and contrast. 'Now I'm placing a seven French by seven, sorry, four centimeter Cook Zimman double pigtail biliary plastic stent across the bile duct. 'The stent is deployed successfully with good bile drainage noted. ' Now I'm withdrawing the scope. 'The scope is out. 'This concludes the procedure. 'Estimated blood loss is none. 'No specimens are obtained and there are no immediate complications. 'End of test four.

'Double wire technique is attempted but initially unsuccessful. 'Cancellation of the pancreatic duct occurred before successful biliary access. ' Pre-cut sphincterotomy is performed. 'It facilitates bile duct access using a sphincterotome. 'A guide wire is left in the pancreatic duct. 'So the second wire is used to achieve deep bile duct annulation. ' Cholangiogram shows bile leak that is extravasation from the right intrahepatic branches. 'I see no intrahepatic or extrahepatic ductal dilation. 'The cystic duct and the gallbladder opacified normally. ' biliary sphincterotomy is performed and a 9 to 12 mm balloon was advanced into the right intrahepatic duct up to the site of the leak seven french into 12 centimeter boston scientific advenix rapid urinal bend plastic biliary stent is successfully placed across the leak site ' and a 5 French into 3 centimeter plastic pancreatic duct stent is deployed into the main pancreatic duct for post-ARCP pancreatitis prophylaxis. 'I see the contrast drainage is excellent. 'This was a technically difficult ARCP. 'Now I am ' Withdrawing the scope. 'The scope is out. 'The patient tolerated the procedure well. 'Estimated blood loss none. 'Specimens were not obtained. 'There were no immediate complications. 'End of test 5.
